<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16084</anchor> <rss>jms-00CN.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CN</addr>  <route>jms-00CN.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter> 
<p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T} \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>. The <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar{X}</tex> <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced by</link> <tex>X</tex> can be equipped with the structure of a <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> by defining <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ s _{ \bar{X} } }} { X }</tex> to be the following map:</p><center><img src="resources/db2dafd9f200a74eb5cb06e857e699d7-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16085</anchor> <rss>jms-00CM.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00CM</addr>  <route>jms-00CM.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors> <contributor><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></contributor></authors> <title>Successor algebras</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>16086</anchor> <rss>jms-00C9.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C9</addr>  <route>jms-00C9.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>. A <em>successor algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> together with a morphism <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ s _{ X } }} { X }</tex> in <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> called the <em>successor map</em>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>16087</anchor> <rss>jms-00CA.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CA</addr>  <route>jms-00CA.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Homomorphism of successor algebras</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A homomorphism of <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebras</link> is a <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">monad algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ h }} { Y }</tex> that preserves the successor operation:</p><center><img src="resources/c35c433d21943fb3ea5fe76a404b1e04-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>16088</anchor> <rss>jms-00CC.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CC</addr>  <route>jms-00CC.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The successor restriction of a successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be an <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>. We define the <em>successor restriction</em> of <tex>X</tex> to be the <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> <tex>s \cdot X  : \equiv   s _{ X } \cdot  X</tex> defined by <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restricting</link> <tex>X</tex> along its successor map.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>16089</anchor> <rss>jms-00CN.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CN</addr>  <route>jms-00CN.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter> 
<p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T} \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>. The <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar{X}</tex> <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced by</link> <tex>X</tex> can be equipped with the structure of a <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> by defining <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ s _{ \bar{X} } }} { X }</tex> to be the following map:</p><center><img src="resources/db2dafd9f200a74eb5cb06e857e699d7-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>5</crumb></trail> <anchor>16090</anchor> <rss>jms-00CR.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CR</addr>  <route>jms-00CR.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { s \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar{I} } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar{I}</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>s \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">successor restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   We have <link href="jms-00CK.xml" type="local" title="Lifting homomorphisms to the induced monad algebra">already seen</link> that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { s \cdot X }</tex> tracks an <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar{I} } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { X }</tex>. It remains to show that this homomorphism preserves the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">successor operation</link>.
  <ol>    <li>      We first unfold the successor operation of the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> on <tex>I</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/726480d09e49fab8ac7eeaa0d715566d-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Then we use the algebra property of <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { s \cdot X }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/db5addfd011ad105a8f15c3d643ef866-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Then we unfold the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">restricted algebra structure</link>.
      <center><img src="resources/f7f07991b5b0215ca2bb709a32ab136e-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Finally we the unitality of the <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>X</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/d2fe56a4ef7b52c1dd0d108af9fa8f0d-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16091</anchor> <rss>jms-00C5.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C5</addr>  <route>jms-00C5.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}   \equiv   { \left ( T, \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>. An <em>algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor"><tex>T</tex>-algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> satisfying the following unit and associativity laws:</p><center><img src="resources/ec6759e00f9145acf5448e10c3d94449-web.svg"/></center><center><img src="resources/146c1fca85ae1729922b71100b2a58a7-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16092</anchor> <rss>jms-00C9.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C9</addr>  <route>jms-00C9.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>. A <em>successor algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> together with a morphism <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ s _{ X } }} { X }</tex> in <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> called the <em>successor map</em>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16093</anchor> <rss>jms-00CD.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CD</addr>  <route>jms-00CD.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> that is a fixed point, i.e. the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. We may define the <em>induced <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>-algebra</em> <tex>\bar{X}</tex> to have the same carrier object as <tex>X</tex>  and with the algebra map <tex>{ T X } \xrightarrow{{ \alpha _{ \bar{X} } }} { X }</tex> defined as follows:
  <center><img src="resources/388a9d5ed5c889741a26879c822bf4b9-web.svg"/></center></p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16094</anchor> <rss>jms-00C8.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C8</addr>  <route>jms-00C8.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Weak algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We shall refer to an <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebra</link> for the underlying endofunctor of a monad as a <em>weak algebra</em>, following <link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">Joyal and Moerdijk</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16095</anchor> <rss>jms-00CR.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CR</addr>  <route>jms-00CR.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { s \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar{I} } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar{I}</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>s \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">successor restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   We have <link href="jms-00CK.xml" type="local" title="Lifting homomorphisms to the induced monad algebra">already seen</link> that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { s \cdot X }</tex> tracks an <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar{I} } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { X }</tex>. It remains to show that this homomorphism preserves the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">successor operation</link>.
  <ol>    <li>      We first unfold the successor operation of the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> on <tex>I</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/726480d09e49fab8ac7eeaa0d715566d-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Then we use the algebra property of <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { s \cdot X }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/db5addfd011ad105a8f15c3d643ef866-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Then we unfold the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">restricted algebra structure</link>.
      <center><img src="resources/f7f07991b5b0215ca2bb709a32ab136e-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Finally we the unitality of the <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>X</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/d2fe56a4ef7b52c1dd0d108af9fa8f0d-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>